english:
  title: Epitaph for Minister Na, Lord of Geumseong, Upper Guard of the Royal Household and Counselor-in-Chief
  author: Lee Je-hyeon
  language: eng
  text: |-
    In the fourth year of Zhizheng, the eighth month on the day of Gichuk in 1344, Minister Na, Counselor-in-Chief and Upper Guard of the Royal Household, passed from this world. The king commanded the proper officials to pay their respects, and bestowed upon him the posthumous name of "Good Integrity." That same year, in the eleventh month on the day of Gyeongbin, he was buried according to rites on the northern hill beyond the Yaksa Temple in Songnim County.

    The Minister's given name was Ikhui. He was of Naju lineage, the eleventh-generation descendant of Cho-rye, Great Pillar of the Three Han Kingdoms. His great-grandfather Hyojeon received imperial appointment as Grand Master for Emoluments and Minister of Rites. His grandfather Dekhwang, having served as Keeper of the Privy Seal and Minister of Rites with the rank of Golden Robes, retired with honor. His father, Yuan-bin, held office as Protector of the Military and Inspector of the War Office, and his mother was the daughter of Minister Munchu of the Zhao clan, a woman of distinguished bearing.

    The Minister took a wife, the daughter of Minister Min Jye, a learned scholar known as Muxian. They bore two children: a daughter who married the noble Choi Mundu, and a son, Younggyeol, now serving as Deputy Commander of the Secret Chancellery.

    Born into a military family, the Minister trained in the martial arts from youth and had little time for books. Yet his nature was upright and resolute; he admired integrity and found shame in contention with others. When his mother divided the family estate and set aside forty slaves for his portion, he refused, saying: "As a single son among five daughters, how could I bring myself to accept this excess and burden the household with want?" His mother, moved by his virtue, agreed to his request.

    At seventeen, he received the imperial commission and bearing the gold seal, became Upper Commandant of a Thousand. Upon his father's passing, he inherited the rank of Commander of Ten Thousand, with the military title of Tiger General and authority over three commanders. In the final years of King Chungnyeol, he was appointed to the Spirit Tiger Guard and granted the fish seal of Counselor.

    When the court undertook sweeping reforms, most officials were dismissed. Yet the Minister alone was retained, for his steadfast judgment proved invaluable. Though many of rank and power cast dark glances upon him when he questioned and sent back improper edicts, he remained unmoved. Ten years passed in disfavor before he was restored as Inspector of the Gate Guard. After seven more years of service in various posts, he rose to the rank of Counselor-in-Chief and was enfeoffed Lord of Geumseong.

    At fifty-seven, he passed his title to his son and retired to a life of quiet contemplation for seventeen years more. Often he would walk alone through his garden, troubled by thoughts of the people's welfare and the proper use of talent. He had served once as magistrate of Gyerim and thrice as commander of Happo, earning praise for his frugality, diligence, and compassion.

    When the present king ascended and took up governance, the Minister was called again to serve as Counselor-in-Chief, becoming one of the Five Ministers whom the realm spoke of with reverence.

    Though his face had grown lean and his hearing had dimmed with age, when matters of state demanded his attention, his spirit remained keen and his resolve unwavering. One day he spoke thus to Minister Lee Jehyeon: "Our young king has entrusted all to his ministers. Yet those unfit for their station have not learned from past mistakes. I would withdraw and not share in the condemnation that must follow." Minister Lee replied: "I have offered counsel thrice over, yet seen it go unheeded. I lack the courage to depart. How could I not follow your wisdom?"

    Ten days later, word came that the Minister had taken ill and would retire. I assumed he meant to act upon his resolve. But alas—who could have known he would not rise again? I hastened to pay my respects and grieve, yet soon his sons and son-in-law came seeking this humble epitaph to inscribe upon stone and place within his tomb. Bound by duty and affection, I could not refuse.

    Let this epitaph speak:

    A minister of grace and mercy,
    A general of honor and shame,
    He sought only what was right,
    Undaunted by power's threats.

    All virtue came from his nature,
    No learning was required to perfect it—
    Yet had he borne sword and feathered arrows,
    His deeds would have reached no further.

    What am I, that fortune granted
    Late friendship with such a man?
    How could I betray a single word
    And claim he merely died?
